article.description:
Ricky Davis scored 26 points, grabbed a key rebound and sank two clutch
free throws to lead the Wolves to a 96-92 win over the Houston
Rockets on Friday night.
article.headline: Davis scores 26, leads Wolves to win in debut
article.linkText: Davis scores 26, leads Wolves to win in debut
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Ricky Davis was a welcome addition to the lineup for the Minnesota Timberwolves. The day after he was traded from Boston in a seven-player swap, Davis scored 26 points, grabbed a key rebound and sank two clutch free throws to lead the Wolves to a 96-92 win over the Houston Rockets on Friday night. Davis hit 10 of 18 shots, the last one a jumper from the wing with 1:08 left that put Minnesota up 92-88. Stromile Swift sank two free throws with 59.8 seconds left and Marko Jaric missed at the other end, giving the Rockets a chance to tie. Tracy McGrady got the ball and Davis guarded him tightly, forcing McGrady into an off-balance miss. Kevin Garnett rebounded and split two free throws with 14.4 seconds left to make it 93-90. David Wesley missed a 3-pointer and Davis grabbed the rebound. He sank two free throws with 8.1 seconds left to help his new squad win for just the second time in six games. McGrady, who played the first half with a facemask to protect his bruised nose, scored 19 for Houston. Swift, sidelined the last nine games with an eye infection, also had 19. Garnett scored 26 points and grabbed 12 rebounds for Minnesota, which had lost each of its last two games by at least 20 points. The 19-21 start prompted Thursday's trade, which brought Davis, Mark Blount, Marcus Banks, Justin Reed and two conditional second-round draft picks to Minnesota. Blount was the only other one of the four who played, scoring four points. Wally Szczerbiak, centers Dwayne Jones and Michael Olowokandi and a future first-round draft pick went to Boston. Davis, who had started all 42 games with Boston before the trade, was averaging 19.7 points and 5.3 assists. He flew to Houston, passed a physical and spent an hour reviewing Minnesota's playbook before the game. Davis showed no ill effects of his hectic day, though, hitting five of his first eight shots. The Rockets were sharp, too, starting 7-for-10 and leading 27-25 after the opening quarter. But after their highest-scoring first quarter at the Toyota Center all season, the Rockets went cold and Rashad McCants got rolling. The rookie from North Carolina scored a career high 16 points on 7-of-9 shooting in the second quarter. After the quick start, the Rockets missed 26 of their next 35 shots and trailed 56-42 two minutes into the second half. McGrady, flustered by a 4-for-11 start, ripped off the facemask and tossed it to the bench with 9:42 left in the third quarter. McGrady hurt his nose on Wednesday, taking an inadvertent elbow from Charlotte's Jake Voskuhl. While his nose wasn't broken, McGrady said he'll probably wear the mask for a few games. The Rockets rediscovered their early shooting touch and finished the third quarter with a 12-2 spurt. McGrady swished a 3-pointer with 9:43 left to make it 71-all, the first of four ties in the fourth quarter.

Game notes
Rockets F Juwan Howard sat out because of flu symptoms. Howard is the 11th player on the current roster to miss a game because of illness or injury. ...The road team has won six of the last seven meetings between the teams. ... Houston C Yao Ming, who's missed 18 games since undergoing toe surgery on Dec. 19, says he'll return to the lineup next week. "Everything is going well," Yao said. "I'm getting close."
